Rhinoviruses are antigenically diverse members of the family 
 Picornaviridae, genus 
 Enterovirus, that cause the common cold (

  1
 ). Rhinovirus C causes an estimated 50% of all human upper respiratory tract infections (

  1
 ) and most acute exacerbations of asthma in children (

  2
 ). More than 160 distinct rhinovirus genotypes have been identified in human populations globally, and extensive antigenic heterogeneity limits cross-protective immunity (

  3
 ). Accordingly, persons typically acquire several rhinovirus infections annually throughout childhood and continue to acquire new infections throughout adulthood (

  4
 ).
